<h2>
    Fishing Techniques That Work
</h2>
<h3>
    Bank Fishing Tips
</h3>
<p>
    For those fishing without a boat, bank access is plentiful near Salem. Some tips for success include:
</p>
<ul>
    <li>
        Use bait such as salmon eggs, cured shrimp, or sardines.
    </li>
    <li>
        Cast near river seams or behind obstructions where salmon rest.
    </li>
    <li>
        Fish early in the morning or late in the evening when salmon are more active.
    </li>
</ul>
<p>
    Local hot spots like Wallace Marine Park and Independence Landing offer easy access and productive waters for shore-bound anglers.
</p>
<h3>
    Boat Trolling Techniques
</h3>
<p>
    Trolling is one of the most effective ways to target Chinook in deeper river channels. Here’s how to maximize your chances:
</p>
<ul>
    <li>
        Use herring or anchovies with a flasher setup.
    </li>
    <li>
        Troll at slow speeds (1.5-2.5 mph) near river mouths and bends.
    </li>
    <li>
        Depth finders help identify the salmon’s location in the water column.
    </li>
</ul>
<h3>
    Back-Bouncing and Plunking Methods
</h3>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Back-bouncing</strong> involves drifting bait near the riverbed from a boat. It’s ideal in deeper pools.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Plunking</strong> is perfect for slower waters and involves stationary setups with bait suspended just off the bottom.
    </li>
</ul>
<p>
    Both methods are productive during higher river flows in early spring and late fall.
</p>
