</h2>
<h3>
    How to Fillet a Chinook
</h3>
<p>
    After a successful day on the water, knowing how to properly clean and fillet your Chinook is crucial. Follow these steps:
</p>
<ol>
    <li>
        Lay the salmon on its side and make a cut behind the gills down to the backbone.
    </li>
    <li>
        Turn your knife flat and follow the spine to the tail in a smooth motion.
    </li>
    <li>
        Flip the fish and repeat on the other side.
    </li>
    <li>
        Remove rib bones and trim belly fat for a clean fillet.
    </li>
</ol>
<p>
    Keep your knife sharp and a clean surface ready to reduce waste and keep the meat fresh.
</p>
<h3>
    Best Grilling and Smoking Recipes
</h3>
<p>
    Chinook salmon is rich, oily, and perfect for a variety of preparations:
</p>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Grilling:</strong> Season with garlic, lemon, and herbs. Grill skin-side down for 10–15 minutes.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Smoking:</strong> Use alder or applewood chips. Brine your fillets for 6–8 hours before smoking.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Pan-seared:</strong> A quick and easy way to enjoy the rich flavor without overcooking.
    </li>
</ul>
<p>
    Serve with roasted vegetables or wild rice for a wholesome Oregon-style meal.
